---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "15 Best Cheap Stocks to Buy Now (Under $20) | Westmount Fundamentals",
  description: "Looking for high-upside stocks trading at a low share price? We screened the market for fundamentally sound companies trading under $20. See the list.",
  category: "list",
  published: "2024-07-01",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": meta.title,
      "description": meta.description,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Fundamentals"
      },
      "publisher": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Fundamentals",
        "logo": {
          "@type": "ImageObject",
          "url": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/logo.png"
        }
      },
      "datePublished": meta.published
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does a low share price mean a stock is cheap?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "No. A stock's share price simply reflects the company's total value (market capitalization) divided by the number of shares outstanding. A $5 stock can be incredibly expensive if the company makes no money, while a $500 stock can be cheap if it generates massive profits."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Are cheap stocks under $20 safe?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "They carry higher risk. Many companies trade under $20 because they are small-cap stocks, recent IPOs, or established companies facing serious fundamental issues. However, our list filters for companies with strong balance sheets to mitigate this risk."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I get rich buying penny stocks?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "While penny stocks (typically trading under $5) can offer massive percentage gains, they are highly speculative, often illiquid, and prone to manipulation. We generally recommend sticking to stocks listed on major exchanges with proven revenues."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why do some people prefer cheap stocks?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Psychology plays a big role. It 'feels' better to own 100 shares of a $10 stock than 1 share of a $1,000 stock. Additionally, smaller companies trading at low share prices often have more runway for explosive percentage growth compared to mature mega-caps."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is a stock split?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "When a company's share price gets too high, they may execute a stock split (e.g., 2-for-1). If you owned 1 share at $100, you now own 2 shares at $50. The total value remains exactly the same, but the lower share price can make the stock more accessible to retail investors."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/best-cheap-stocks-to-buy-now" schema={JSON.stringify(schema)}>
  <div class="page-content container">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>15 Best Cheap Stocks to Buy Now (Under $20)</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Looking past the $500-per-share mega-caps, we screened the market for fundamentally sound companies trading at accessible price points.</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>The Allure of the Accessible Share Price</h2>
      <p>
        Let’s start with an essential rule of investing: <strong>A low share price does not necessarily mean a company is "cheap."</strong> A company's share price simply reflects its total market capitalization divided by the number of shares outstanding. A company trading at $5 per share could have a massive market cap if it has issued billions of shares.
      </p>
      <p>
        However, psychology plays a significant role in retail investing. It intuitively feels better to own 100 shares of a $15 stock than a fractional share of a $1,500 stock. Furthermore, many companies trading at low absolute share prices are small-to-mid-cap (SMID) companies. These businesses often have a far longer runway for massive, multi-bagger percentage growth compared to mature, trillion-dollar mega-caps.
      </p>
      <p>
        The danger lies in "penny stocks" (typically under $5), which are often plagued by horrible balance sheets, massive dilution, and pump-and-dump schemes. For our list of the best cheap stocks, we instituted strict quality filters: a share price under $20, positive operating cash flow, manageable debt, and a listing on a major exchange (NYSE or NASDAQ). If you are looking for stocks that are "cheap" based on fundamental valuation rather than just share price, consider exploring our list of the <a href="/best-undervalued-stocks-2025" style="color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: underline;">best undervalued stocks for 2025</a>, or look into specific sectors with our guide to <a href="/best-uranium-stocks" style="color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: underline;">the best uranium stocks</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

