    <section class="ranked-list">
      <h2>The Top 15 Cheap Stocks (Under $20)</h2>

      <div class="card" id="rank-1">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">1</div>
          <h3>Palantir Technologies (PLTR)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Technology / AI Data</p>
          <p><strong>Est. Price:</strong> ~$25 (Recently broke out)</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          While Palantir recently broke out above our $20 threshold, it remains one of the premier examples of a high-quality company that traded in the teens for an extended period. As enterprise adoption of AI explodes, Palantir's Artificial Intelligence Platform (AIP) has driven massive re-acceleration in their commercial revenue segment. With GAAP profitability achieved and S&P 500 inclusion secured, it represents the gold standard for high-growth tech at an accessible price point.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Dominant moat in government defense analytics.</li>
              <li>Rapidly accelerating US Commercial revenue growth.</li>
              <li>Consistently GAAP profitable with zero debt.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Valuation is currently priced for perfection.</li>
              <li>Heavy reliance on lumpy government contracts.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-2">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">2</div>
          <h3>SoFi Technologies (SOFI)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Financials / FinTech</p>
          <p><strong>Est. Price:</strong> ~$7 - $10</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          SoFi went public via SPAC during the 2021 boom and crashed spectacularly shortly after. However, the underlying business has executed flawlessly. Having secured a national bank charter, SoFi offers high-yield savings, personal loans, and a growing tech platform (Galileo). They recently achieved GAAP profitability and are rapidly growing their high-quality member base. At sub-$10, it represents an aggressive growth play in the fintech sector.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Bank charter provides access to low-cost deposit funding.</li>
              <li>Consistently beating revenue and membership growth targets.</li>
              <li>Transitioning successfully beyond just student loan refinancing.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Heavy reliance on personal loans, which carry higher default risk.</li>
              <li>Highly sensitive to interest rate fluctuations.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-3">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">3</div>
          <h3>Kinder Morgan (KMI)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Energy Infrastructure</p>
          <p><strong>Est. Price:</strong> ~$19 - $21</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Kinder Morgan is one of the largest energy infrastructure companies in North America, controlling a massive network of natural gas pipelines. Unlike oil explorers, pipeline companies operate like toll roads, collecting steady fees regardless of commodity price volatility. Trading around $20, KMI offers a highly defensive, toll-road business model paying a massive dividend yield.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Highly predictable, fee-based cash flow ("toll road" model).</li>
              <li>Massive dividend yield supported by operating cash.</li>
              <li>Critical infrastructure required for the ongoing natural gas transition.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Very slow top-line growth.</li>
              <li>High debt load typical of the infrastructure sector.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-4">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">4</div>
          <h3>Warner Bros. Discovery (WBD)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Consumer / Media</p>
          <p><strong>Est. Price:</strong> ~$8 - $11</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Created through the merger of WarnerMedia and Discovery, WBD was born with an incredible library of IP (HBO, DC Universe, Harry Potter) and an absolutely crushing debt load. CEO David Zaslav has spent the last two years ruthlessly cutting costs and paying down debt to stabilize the business. Trading at a fraction of its intrinsic IP value, WBD is a high-risk, high-reward deep value turnaround play.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>World-class content library and IP portfolio.</li>
              <li>Direct-to-consumer (Max) streaming segment is actually profitable.</li>
              <li>Aggressive debt reduction is ahead of schedule.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Legacy linear TV networks are in terminal decline.</li>
              <li>Still carries a massive, restrictive debt burden.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-5">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">5</div>
          <h3>AGNC Investment Corp. (AGNC)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Real Estate Investment Trust (mREIT)</p>
          <p><strong>Est. Price:</strong> ~$9 - $11</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          AGNC is a mortgage REIT, meaning it borrows short-term money to buy long-term mortgage-backed securities (MBS) guaranteed by the US government. They make money on the interest rate spread. The rapidly rising interest rate environment of 2022-2023 crushed their book value, but as rates stabilize or fall, AGNC is positioned for significant book value recovery while paying a staggering double-digit monthly dividend.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Massive double-digit dividend yield paid monthly.</li>
              <li>Invests almost exclusively in agency-backed MBS (zero credit risk).</li>
              <li>Poised for book value expansion as interest rates fall.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Highly leveraged business model.</li>
              <li>Extremely sensitive to interest rate volatility and spread widening.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-6">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">6</div>
          <h3>KeyCorp (KEY)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Financials</p>
          <p><strong>Est. Price:</strong> ~$13 - $16</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          A major U.S. regional bank that saw its share price devastated during the 2023 banking panic. However, KEY's underlying deposit base proved sticky. As older, low-yielding assets roll off their balance sheet, Net Interest Income is expected to rebound sharply, making the stock cheap relative to its historical premium valuation.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>High-quality commercial banking franchise.</li>
              <li>Significant earnings leverage as interest rates normalize.</li>
              <li>Attractive dividend yield.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Regional banks remain highly sensitive to macro-economic fears.</li>
              <li>Slower loan growth in the current rate environment.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-7">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">7</div>
          <h3>Marqeta Inc. (MQ)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Technology / FinTech</p>
          <p><strong>Est. Price:</strong> ~$5 - $7</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Marqeta provides the backend card-issuing infrastructure for major fintechs like Block (Cash App), Affirm, and Uber. While customer concentration risk with Block remains high, the company is growing total processing volume rapidly and holds a massive cash pile with zero debt.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Massive net-cash balance sheet (over $1B).</li>
              <li>Modern, API-first technology displacing legacy providers.</li>
              <li>Strong total processing volume (TPV) growth.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Extreme customer concentration (Block accounts for ~70% of revenue).</li>
              <li>GAAP un-profitable due to high stock-based compensation.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-8">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">8</div>
          <h3>GoodRx Holdings (GDRX)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Healthcare</p>
          <p><strong>Est. Price:</strong> ~$6 - $8</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          GoodRx operates a platform to help consumers find the lowest prices for prescription drugs. The stock crashed after a major dispute with a grocery chain partner, but they have since restructured contracts, returned to profitability, and expanded their manufacturer solutions business.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>High margin, asset-light software business.</li>
              <li>Strong consumer brand awareness for prescription savings.</li>
              <li>Growing manufacturer solutions segment diversifies revenue.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Vulnerable to disputes with major pharmacy chains (PBMs).</li>
              <li>Intense competition from Amazon Pharmacy and others.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-9">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">9</div>
          <h3>Energy Transfer LP (ET)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Energy</p>
          <p><strong>Est. Price:</strong> ~$14 - $16</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Operating a massive network of crude, natural gas, and NGL pipelines, ET is structured as a Master Limited Partnership (MLP). It offers an enormous, highly covered distribution yield and recently completed major acquisitions, solidifying its dominant position in the Permian basin.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Massive ~8% distribution yield with strong coverage.</li>
              <li>Diversified, fee-based midstream assets.</li>
              <li>Recent debt reduction improves financial flexibility.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>MLP structure requires a K-1 tax form, which complicates filing.</li>
              <li>Management has a history of aggressive, debt-funded M&A.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-10">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">10</div>
          <h3>Ford Motor Company (F)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Consumer Discretionary</p>
          <p><strong>Est. Price:</strong> ~$11 - $13</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          Ford is navigating an incredibly complex, capital-intensive transition to electric vehicles (EVs). While the EV segment is currently losing billions, the legacy internal combustion engine (ICE) business and Ford Pro (commercial vehicles) are cash flow machines, supporting a strong dividend while trading under $15.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Ford Pro (commercial fleet) is a high-margin, dominant business.</li>
              <li>Strong dividend yield while waiting for the EV transition to stabilize.</li>
              <li>F-Series truck remains the best-selling vehicle in America.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Massive, ongoing losses in the "Model e" (EV) division.</li>
              <li>Highly cyclical business vulnerable to a consumer recession.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-11">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">11</div>
          <h3>IonQ Inc. (IONQ)</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="card-stats">
          <p><strong>Sector:</strong> Technology</p>
          <p><strong>Est. Price:</strong> ~$10 - $14</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          A pure-play quantum computing hardware company. Trading under $15, it is highly speculative and years away from profitability. However, IonQ consistently hits its technical milestones and represents a "moonshot" bet on the next era of computing power beyond AI.
        </p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>Pros</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Pure-play exposure to the potentially revolutionary quantum computing sector.</li>
              <li>Consistently achieving internal technical roadmaps.</li>
              <li>Strong cash position to fund operations for several years.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Cons</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Extreme early-stage risk; commercially viable quantum computing is years away.</li>
              <li>Zero profitability and highly volatile share price.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card" id="rank-12">
        <div class="card-header">
          <div class="rank-badge">12</div>
