    <section>
      <h2>Screening Methodology for Cheap Stocks</h2>
      <p>
        When evaluating stocks trading under $20, avoiding total wipeouts is more important than finding the absolute highest upside. Our screening process focuses on fundamental survivability:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Liquidity & Solvency:</strong> We eliminate companies with an impending cash crunch. The company must have enough cash on hand to fund operations or a clear path to raising capital without massive, punitive shareholder dilution.</li>
        <li><strong>Revenue Generation:</strong> With the exception of early-stage biotech or pure deep-tech plays (like Quantum), we require companies to generate real, proven revenue. We avoid pre-revenue "concept" stocks.</li>
        <li><strong>Exchange Listing:</strong> We strictly limit our picks to companies listed on the NYSE or NASDAQ. Over-The-Counter (OTC) or "Pink Sheet" stocks lack the rigorous financial reporting requirements needed to protect retail investors.</li>
        <li><strong>Path to Profitability:</strong> If a company is currently losing money, there must be a clearly defined, mathematically logical path to GAAP profitability within the next 24-36 months.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>Does a low share price mean a stock is cheap?</summary>
        <p>
          No. A stock's share price simply reflects the company's total value (market capitalization) divided by the number of shares outstanding. A $5 stock can be incredibly expensive if the company makes no money, while a $500 stock can be cheap if it generates massive profits.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Are cheap stocks under $20 safe?</summary>
        <p>
          They carry higher risk. Many companies trade under $20 because they are small-cap stocks, recent IPOs, or established companies facing serious fundamental issues. However, our list filters for companies with strong balance sheets to mitigate this risk.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can I get rich buying penny stocks?</summary>
        <p>
          While penny stocks (typically trading under $5) can offer massive percentage gains, they are highly speculative, often illiquid, and prone to manipulation. We generally recommend sticking to stocks listed on major exchanges with proven revenues.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why do some people prefer cheap stocks?</summary>
        <p>
          Psychology plays a big role. It 'feels' better to own 100 shares of a $10 stock than 1 share of a $1,000 stock. Additionally, smaller companies trading at low share prices often have more runway for explosive percentage growth compared to mature mega-caps.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What is a stock split?</summary>
        <p>
          When a company's share price gets too high, they may execute a stock split (e.g., 2-for-1). If you owned 1 share at $100, you now own 2 shares at $50. The total value remains exactly the same, but the lower share price can make the stock more accessible to retail investors.
        </p>
      </details>
    </section>
